--- title: German Credit Series - Tuning author: - name: Martin Binder - name: Florian Pfisterer date: 03-11-2020 categories: - tuning - resampling - classification description: | Optimize Hyperparameters and apply nested resampling. aliases: - ../../../gallery/2020-03-11-mlr3tuning-tutorial-german-credit/index.html - ../../../gallery/series/2020-03-11-mlr3tuning-tutorial-german-credit/index.html --- # Intro This is the second part of a serial of tutorials. The other parts of this series can be found here: - [Part I - Basics](/gallery/basic/2020-03-11-basics-german-credit/) - [Part III - Pipelines](/gallery/basic/2020-03-11-mlr3pipelines-tutorial-german-credit/) We will continue working with the German credit dataset. In Part I, we peeked into the dataset by using and comparing some learners with their default parameters. We will now see how to: - Tune hyperparameters for a given problem - Perform nested resampling # Prerequisites First, load the packages we are going to use: ::: {.cell layout-align="center"} ```{.r .cell-code} library("mlr3verse") library("data.table") library("mlr3tuning") library("ggplot2") ``` ::: We initialize the random number generator with a fixed seed for reproducibility, and decrease the verbosity of the logger to keep the output clearly represented. ::: {.cell layout-align="center"} ```{.r .cell-code} set.seed(7832) lgr::get_logger("mlr3")$set_threshold("warn") lgr::get_logger("bbotk")$set_threshold("warn") ``` ::: We use the same [`Task`](https://mlr3.mlr-org.com/reference/Task.html) as in Part I: ::: {.cell layout-align="center"} ```{.r .cell-code} task = tsk("german_credit") ``` ::: We also might want to use multiple cores to reduce long run times of tuning runs. ::: {.cell layout-align="center"} ```{.r .cell-code} future::plan("multiprocess") ``` ::: ## Evaluation We will evaluate all hyperparameter configurations using 10-fold cross-validation. We use a *fixed* train-test split, i.e. the same splits for each evaluation. Otherwise, some evaluation could get unusually "hard" splits, which would make comparisons unfair. ::: {.cell layout-align="center"} ```{.r .cell-code} cv10 = rsmp("cv", folds = 10) # fix the train-test splits using the $instantiate() method cv10$instantiate(task) # have a look at the test set instances per fold cv10$instance ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` row_id fold 1: 18 1 2: 19 1 3: 35 1 4: 38 1 5: 55 1 --- 996: 973 10 997: 975 10 998: 981 10 999: 993 10 1000: 998 10 ``` ::: ::: # Simple Parameter Tuning Parameter tuning in [mlr3](https://mlr3.mlr-org.com) needs two packages: 1. The [paradox](https://paradox.mlr-org.com) package is used for the search space definition of the hyperparameters. 1. The [mlr3tuning](https://mlr3tuning.mlr-org.com) package is used for tuning the hyperparameters. The packages are loaded by the [mlr3verse](https://mlr3verse.mlr-org.com) package. ## Search Space and Problem Definition First, we need to decide what [`Learner`](https://mlr3.mlr-org.com/reference/Learner.html) we want to optimize. We will use [`LearnerClassifKKNN`](https://mlr3learners.mlr-org.com/reference/mlr_learners_classif.kknn.html), the "kernelized" k-nearest neighbor classifier. We will use `kknn` as a normal kNN without weighting first (i.e., using the rectangular kernel): ::: {.cell layout-align="center"} ```{.r .cell-code} knn = lrn("classif.kknn", predict_type = "prob", kernel = "rectangular") ``` ::: As a next step, we decide what parameters we optimize over. Before that, though, we are interested in the parameter set on which we could tune: ::: {.cell layout-align="center"} ```{.r .cell-code} knn$param_set ``` ::: ::: {.cell layout-align="center"} ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` id class lower upper nlevels 1: k ParamInt 1 Inf Inf 2: distance ParamDbl 0 Inf Inf 3: kernel ParamFct NA NA 10 4: scale ParamLgl NA NA 2 5: ykernel ParamUty NA NA Inf 6: store_model ParamLgl NA NA 2 ``` ::: ::: We first tune the `k` parameter (i.e. the number of nearest neighbors), between 3 to 20. Second, we tune the `distance` function, allowing L1 and L2 distances. To do so, we use the `paradox` package to define a search space (see the [online vignette](https://mlr3book.mlr-org.com/paradox.html) for a more complete introduction. ::: {.cell layout-align="center"} ```{.r .cell-code} search_space = ps( k = p_int(3, 20), distance = p_int(1, 2) ) ``` ::: As a next step, we define a [`TuningInstanceSingleCrit`](https://mlr3tuning.mlr-org.com/reference/TuningInstanceSingleCrit.html) that represents the problem we are trying to optimize. ::: {.cell layout-align="center"} ```{.r .cell-code} instance_grid = TuningInstanceSingleCrit$new( task = task, learner = knn, resampling = cv10, measure = msr("classif.ce"), terminator = trm("none"), search_space = search_space ) ``` ::: ## Grid Search After having set up a tuning instance, we can start tuning. Before that, we need a tuning strategy, though. A simple tuning method is to try all possible combinations of parameters: **Grid Search**. While it is very intuitive and simple, it is inefficient if the search space is large. For this simple use case, it suffices, though. We get the [`grid_search tuner`](https://mlr3tuning.mlr-org.com/reference/mlr_tuners_grid_search.html) via: ::: {.cell layout-align="center"} ```{.r .cell-code} tuner_grid = tnr("grid_search", resolution = 18, batch_size = 36) ``` ::: Tuning works by calling `$optimize()`. Note that the tuning procedure *modifies* our tuning instance (as usual for `R6` class objects). The result can be found in the `instance` object. Before tuning it is empty: ::: {.cell layout-align="center"} ```{.r .cell-code} instance_grid$result ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` NULL ``` ::: ::: Now, we tune: ::: {.cell layout-align="center"} ```{.r .cell-code} tuner_grid$optimize(instance_grid) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` k distance learner_param_vals x_domain classif.ce 1: 7 1 0.25 ``` ::: ::: The result is returned by `$optimize()` together with its performance. It can be also accessed with the `$result` slot: ::: {.cell layout-align="center"} ```{.r .cell-code} instance_grid$result ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` k distance learner_param_vals x_domain classif.ce 1: 7 1 0.25 ``` ::: ::: We can also look at the `Archive` of evaluated configurations: ::: {.cell layout-align="center"} ```{.r .cell-code} head(as.data.table(instance_grid$archive)) ``` ::: ::: {.cell layout-align="center"} ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` k distance classif.ce runtime_learners timestamp batch_nr warnings errors 1: 3 1 0.273 1.458 2023-10-30 15:10:10 1 0 0 2: 3 2 0.280 0.435 2023-10-30 15:10:10 1 0 0 3: 4 1 0.290 0.790 2023-10-30 15:10:10 1 0 0 4: 4 2 0.266 0.658 2023-10-30 15:10:10 1 0 0 5: 5 1 0.268 0.716 2023-10-30 15:10:10 1 0 0 6: 5 2 0.256 0.374 2023-10-30 15:10:10 1 0 0 ``` ::: ::: We plot the performances depending on the sampled `k` and `distance`: ::: {.cell layout-align="center"} ```{.r .cell-code} ggplot(as.data.table(instance_grid$archive), aes(x = k, y = classif.ce, color = as.factor(distance))) + geom_line() + geom_point(size = 3) ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} ![](index_files/figure-html/2020-03-11-mlr3tuning-tutorial-german-credit-018-1.png){fig-align='center' width=672} ::: ::: On average, the Euclidean distance (`distance` = 2) seems to work better. However, there is much randomness introduced by the resampling instance. So you, the reader, may see a different result, when you run the experiment yourself and set a different random seed. For `k`, we find that values between 7 and 13 perform well. ## Random Search and Transformation Let's have a look at a larger search space. For example, we could tune *all* available parameters and limit `k` to large values (50). We also now tune the distance param continuously from 1 to 3 as a double and tune distance kernel and whether we scale the features. We may find two problems when doing so: First, the resulting difference in performance between `k` = 3 and `k` = 4 is probably larger than the difference between `k` = 49 and `k` = 50. While 4 is 33% larger than 3, 50 is only 2 percent larger than 49. To account for this we will use a **transformation function** for `k` and optimize in log-space. We define the range for `k` from `log(3)` to `log(50)` and exponentiate in the transformation. Now, as `k` has become a double instead of an int (in the search space, before transformation), we round it in the `extra_trafo`. ::: {.cell layout-align="center"} ```{.r .cell-code} search_space_large = ps( k = p_dbl(log(3), log(50)), distance = p_dbl(1, 3), kernel = p_fct(c("rectangular", "gaussian", "rank", "optimal")), scale = p_lgl(), .extra_trafo = function(x, param_set) { x$k = round(exp(x$k)) x } ) ``` ::: The second problem is that grid search may (and often will) take a long time. For instance, trying out three different values for `k`, `distance`, `kernel`, and the two values for `scale` will take 54 evaluations. Because of this, we use a different search algorithm, namely the **Random Search**. We need to specify in the *tuning instance* a *termination criterion*. The criterion tells the search algorithm when to stop. Here, we will terminate after 36 evaluations: ::: {.cell layout-align="center"} ```{.r .cell-code} tuner_random = tnr("random_search", batch_size = 36) instance_random = TuningInstanceSingleCrit$new( task = task, learner = knn, resampling = cv10, measure = msr("classif.ce"), terminator = trm("evals", n_evals = 36), search_space = search_space_large ) ``` ::: ::: {.cell layout-align="center"} ```{.r .cell-code} tuner_random$optimize(instance_random) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` k distance kernel scale learner_param_vals x_domain classif.ce 1: 1.683743 1.985146 gaussian TRUE 0.254 ``` ::: ::: Like before, we can review the `Archive`. It includes the points before and after the transformation. The archive includes a column for each parameter the `Tuner` sampled on the search space (values before the transformation) and additional columns with prefix `x_domain_*` that refer to the parameters used by the learner (values after the transformation): ::: {.cell layout-align="center"} ```{.r .cell-code} as.data.table(instance_random$archive) ``` ::: ::: {.cell .column-page layout-align="center"} ::: {.cell-output-display} ```{=html}
``` ::: ::: Let's now investigate the performance by parameters. This is especially easy using visualization: ::: {.cell layout-align="center"} ```{.r .cell-code} ggplot(as.data.table(instance_random$archive), aes(x = x_domain_k, y = classif.ce, color = x_domain_scale)) + geom_point(size = 3) + geom_line() ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} ![](index_files/figure-html/2020-03-11-mlr3tuning-tutorial-german-credit-024-1.png){fig-align='center' width=672} ::: ::: The previous plot suggests that `scale` has a strong influence on performance. For the kernel, there does not seem to be a strong influence: ::: {.cell layout-align="center"} ```{.r .cell-code} ggplot(as.data.table(instance_random$archive), aes(x = x_domain_k, y = classif.ce, color = x_domain_kernel)) + geom_point(size = 3) + geom_line() ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} ![](index_files/figure-html/2020-03-11-mlr3tuning-tutorial-german-credit-025-1.png){fig-align='center' width=672} ::: ::: # Nested Resampling Having determined tuned configurations that seem to work well, we want to find out which performance we can expect from them. However, this may require more than this naive approach: ::: {.cell layout-align="center"} ```{.r .cell-code} instance_random$result_y ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` classif.ce 0.254 ``` ::: ```{.r .cell-code} instance_grid$result_y ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` classif.ce 0.25 ``` ::: ::: The problem associated with evaluating tuned models is *overtuning*. The more we search, the more optimistically biased the associated performance metrics from tuning become. There is a solution to this problem, namely **Nested Resampling**. The [mlr3tuning](https://mlr3tuning.mlr-org.com) package provides an [`AutoTuner`](https://mlr3tuning.mlr-org.com/reference/AutoTuner.html) that acts like our tuning method but is actually a [`Learner`](https://mlr3.mlr-org.com/reference/Learner.html). The `$train()` method facilitates tuning of hyperparameters on the training data, using a resampling strategy (below we use 5-fold cross-validation). Then, we actually train a model with optimal hyperparameters on the whole training data. The [`AutoTuner`](https://mlr3tuning.mlr-org.com/reference/AutoTuner.html) finds the best parameters and uses them for training: ::: {.cell layout-align="center"} ```{.r .cell-code} at_grid = AutoTuner$new( learner = knn, resampling = rsmp("cv", folds = 5), # we can NOT use fixed resampling here measure = msr("classif.ce"), terminator = trm("none"), tuner = tnr("grid_search", resolution = 18), search_space = search_space ) ``` ::: The [`AutoTuner`](https://mlr3tuning.mlr-org.com/reference/AutoTuner.html) behaves just like a regular [`Learner`](https://mlr3.mlr-org.com/reference/Learner.html). It can be used to combine the steps of hyperparameter tuning and model fitting but is especially useful for resampling and *fair* comparison of performance through benchmarking: ::: {.cell layout-align="center"} ```{.r .cell-code} rr = resample(task, at_grid, cv10, store_models = TRUE) ``` ::: We check the inner tuning results for stable hyperparameters. This means that the selected hyperparameters should not vary too much. We might observe unstable models in this example because the small data set and the low number of resampling iterations might introduce too much randomness. Usually, we aim for the selection of stable hyperparameters for all outer training sets. ::: {.cell layout-align="center"} ```{.r .cell-code} extract_inner_tuning_results(rr) ``` ::: ::: {.cell layout-align="center"} ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` iteration k distance classif.ce task_id learner_id resampling_id 1: 1 7 1 0.2588889 german_credit classif.kknn.tuned cv 2: 2 5 2 0.2377778 german_credit classif.kknn.tuned cv 3: 3 10 2 0.2500000 german_credit classif.kknn.tuned cv 4: 4 9 2 0.2488889 german_credit classif.kknn.tuned cv 5: 5 7 2 0.2477778 german_credit classif.kknn.tuned cv 6: 6 8 2 0.2411111 german_credit classif.kknn.tuned cv 7: 7 8 2 0.2688889 german_credit classif.kknn.tuned cv 8: 8 7 2 0.2477778 german_credit classif.kknn.tuned cv 9: 9 7 2 0.2655556 german_credit classif.kknn.tuned cv 10: 10 7 2 0.2455556 german_credit classif.kknn.tuned cv ``` ::: ::: Next, we want to compare the predictive performances estimated on the outer resampling to the inner resampling (`extract_inner_tuning_results(rr)`). Significantly lower predictive performances on the outer resampling indicate that the models with the optimized hyperparameters overfit the data. ::: {.cell layout-align="center"} ```{.r .cell-code} rr$score() ``` ::: ::: {.cell layout-align="center"} ::: {.cell-output-display} ```{=html}
``` ::: ::: The archives of the [`AutoTuner`](https://mlr3tuning.mlr-org.com/reference/AutoTuner.html)s allows us to inspect all evaluated hyperparameters configurations with the associated predictive performances. ::: {.cell layout-align="center"} ```{.r .cell-code} extract_inner_tuning_archives(rr) ``` ::: ::: {.cell .column-page layout-align="center"} ::: {.cell-output-display} ```{=html}
``` ::: ::: We aggregate the performances of all resampling iterations: ::: {.cell layout-align="center"} ```{.r .cell-code} rr$aggregate() ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` classif.ce 0.255 ``` ::: ::: Essentially, this is the performance of a "knn with optimal hyperparameters found by grid search". Note that `at_grid` is not changed since [`resample()`](https://mlr3.mlr-org.com/reference/resample.html) creates a clone for each resampling iteration. The trained [`AutoTuner`](https://mlr3tuning.mlr-org.com/reference/AutoTuner.html) objects can be accessed by using ::: {.cell layout-align="center"} ```{.r .cell-code} rr$learners[[1]] ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` * Model: list * Search Space: id class lower upper nlevels default value 1: k ParamInt 3 20 18 2: distance ParamInt 1 2 2 * Packages: mlr3, mlr3tuning, mlr3learners, kknn * Predict Type: prob * Feature Types: logical, integer, numeric, factor, ordered * Properties: multiclass, twoclass ``` ::: ```{.r .cell-code} rr$learners[[1]]$tuning_result ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` k distance learner_param_vals x_domain classif.ce 1: 7 1 0.2588889 ``` ::: ::: # Appendix ## Example: Tuning With A Larger Budget It is always interesting to look at what could have been. The following dataset contains an optimization run result with 3600 evaluations -- more than above by a factor of 100: ::: {.cell layout-align="center"} ::: ::: {.cell .column-page layout-align="center"} ::: {.cell-output-display} ```{=html}
``` ::: ::: The scale effect is just as visible as before with fewer data: ::: {.cell layout-align="center"} ```{.r .cell-code} ggplot(perfdata, aes(x = x_domain_k, y = classif.ce, color = scale)) + geom_point(size = 2, alpha = 0.3) ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} ![](index_files/figure-html/2020-03-11-mlr3tuning-tutorial-german-credit-039-1.png){fig-align='center' width=672} ::: ::: Now, there seems to be a visible pattern by kernel as well: ::: {.cell layout-align="center"} ```{.r .cell-code} ggplot(perfdata, aes(x = x_domain_k, y = classif.ce, color = kernel)) + geom_point(size = 2, alpha = 0.3) ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} ![](index_files/figure-html/2020-03-11-mlr3tuning-tutorial-german-credit-040-1.png){fig-align='center' width=672} ::: ::: In fact, if we zoom in to `(5, 40)` $\times$ `(0.23, 0.28)` and do decrease smoothing we see that different kernels have their optimum at different values of `k`: ::: {.cell layout-align="center"} ```{.r .cell-code} ggplot(perfdata, aes(x = x_domain_k, y = classif.ce, color = kernel, group = interaction(kernel, scale))) + geom_point(size = 2, alpha = 0.3) + geom_smooth() + xlim(5, 40) + ylim(0.23, 0.28) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula = 'y ~ x' ``` ::: ::: {.cell-output-display} ![](index_files/figure-html/2020-03-11-mlr3tuning-tutorial-german-credit-041-1.png){fig-align='center' width=672} ::: ::: What about the `distance` parameter? If we select all results with `k` between 10 and 20 and plot distance and kernel we see an approximate relationship: ::: {.cell layout-align="center"} ```{.r .cell-code} ggplot(perfdata[x_domain_k > 10 & x_domain_k < 20 & scale == TRUE], aes(x = distance, y = classif.ce, color = kernel)) + geom_point(size = 2) + geom_smooth() ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula = 'y ~ x' ``` ::: ::: {.cell-output-display} ![](index_files/figure-html/2020-03-11-mlr3tuning-tutorial-german-credit-042-1.png){fig-align='center' width=672} ::: ::: In sum our observations are: The `scale` parameter is very influential, and scaling is beneficial. The `distance` type seems to be the least influential. There seems to be an interaction between 'k' and 'kernel'.
